      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my fiddle leaf fig is getting really root bound and im worried about moving it to a bigger pot. what kind of soil should i use and how do i do it without killing it??",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You must be worried, because a fiddle leaf fig is a very particular type of plant that hates being root-bound, and if you move it to a bigger pot without doing it right, you risk killing it.\n\nFirst, let's look at the soil. You need a mix that is airy and drains fast, like a **garden soil** that has been treated with a little bit of **garden lime** to help it break down. If you use regular potting soil, it will be too heavy and will suffocate the roots. You want something like a **garden soil** that is well-draining, perhaps with some perlite or vermiculite added to it, so the roots can breathe.\n\nNow, let's talk about the process. You must be very careful not to damage the roots, because if you do, the plant will not recover. You should dig up the plant gently, making sure to keep the roots intact. Then, you can place the plant in the new pot, filling it with the **garden soil** you prepared.\n\nFinally, you must water it very lightly, just enough to settle the soil around the roots, but not so much that it gets too wet. If",
